<h1 class="hero-h">How much does a fractional CFO cost? <em>The practical answer.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">A plain-English breakdown of what fractional CFOs charge in 2026: the pricing models, what actually drives the number up or down, and how it compares to hiring full-time.</p>
<div class="verdict"><div class="verdict-l">Short answer</div><p class="verdict-p">Fractional CFOs charge $8K to $20K per month for one to two days per week, billed as a flat retainer. Hourly work runs $200 to $400 per hour. A full-time CFO, by comparison, costs $300K to $500K all-in per year.</p></div>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">The three ways fractional CFOs price</h2>
<p class="body">Unlike a software subscription, a fractional CFO is a person selling time and judgment. In 2026, three pricing models dominate:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Monthly retainer ($8K to $20K / month).</strong> The most common model. You agree on a set number of days per week (usually one to two) and pay a flat fee. Predictable, and it keeps the CFO invested in the relationship rather than the clock.</li>
<li><strong>Hourly ($200 to $400 / hour).</strong> Used for lighter or unpredictable workloads. Flexible, but harder to budget, and it can discourage you from calling when you should.</li>
<li><strong>Project / fixed fee.</strong> A defined scope such as a fundraise, an audit, a systems migration, or board-deck preparation, priced as a single number. Good when the work has a clear start and end.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Most $5M to $50M companies land on the monthly retainer because the work is ongoing: month-end close, cash management, forecasting, and board reporting do not stop. For a wider view across every role, see the <a href="/fractional-executive-pricing-guide-2026">fractional executive pricing guide for 2026</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">What drives the number up or down</h2>
<p class="body">Two companies can pay very different fees for a fractional CFO. The main variables:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Hours per week.</strong> The single biggest lever. One day a week is roughly half of two days a week.</li>
<li><strong>Company complexity.</strong> Revenue size, number of entities, inventory, multiple currencies, and how clean your books are to start.</li>
<li><strong>Active events.</strong> A live fundraise, an acquisition, or an audit raises both the hours and the seniority you need, pushing fees toward the top of the range or beyond.</li>
<li><strong>Industry.</strong> SaaS, e-commerce, manufacturing, and professional services each carry different financial models and reporting demands.</li>
<li><strong>Seniority.</strong> A CFO who has taken a company public costs more than one who has run finance at a single $10M business. Match the experience to the problem.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Fractional CFO vs. the alternatives</h2>
<p class="body">The fractional CFO sits between a bookkeeper and a full-time finance chief. Here is the cost ladder for financial help in 2026.</p>
<table class="compare-table">
<thead><tr><th>Option</th><th>Typical cost</th><th>Best when</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Bookkeeper</td><td>$500 to $2,500 / month</td><td>You need transactions recorded and books kept current</td></tr>
<tr><td>Controller</td><td>$120K to $180K / year</td><td>You need accurate close, reporting, and process, not strategy</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fractional CFO</td><td>$8K to $20K / month</td><td>You need senior financial strategy without a full-time salary</td></tr>
<tr><td>Full-time CFO</td><td>$300K to $500K / year all-in</td><td>Finance is complex enough to need a dedicated executive</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p class="body">A controller keeps the numbers right. A CFO decides what the numbers should be and how to act on them: pricing, capital, runway, and the model behind the business. Many companies pair a controller for execution with a fractional CFO for strategy, which is often cheaper and better than a single full-time hire.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">What you actually get for the money</h2>
<p class="body">A fractional CFO retainer typically covers ownership of the work that keeps a company financially sound and fundable:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Financial modeling, forecasting, and scenario planning</li>
<li>Cash-flow management and runway oversight</li>
<li>Board and investor reporting, plus fundraising support</li>
<li>Pricing, unit economics, and margin analysis</li>
<li>Budgeting and KPI design across the leadership team</li>
<li>Oversight of the bookkeeper or controller and the close process</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">If your metrics need a common language first, our glossary covers the fundamentals a CFO will hold you to: <a href="/what-is-annual-recurring-revenue">ARR</a>, <a href="/what-is-net-revenue-retention">net revenue retention</a>, and <a href="/what-is-revenue-churn">revenue churn</a>. And because every Treetop engagement is AI-native, a modern CFO uses <a href="/ai-for-cfos">AI tooling for finance leaders</a> to compress reporting and analysis that used to take days.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Is it worth it?</h2>
<p class="body">The honest test is opportunity cost. A fractional CFO at $12K per month is $144K a year. If that person tightens cash management, sharpens your raise, fixes pricing, or prevents one expensive mistake, the return dwarfs the fee. If your finances are simple and a bookkeeper plus a sharp founder are handling it well, a fractional CFO is premature. The model earns its keep when financial decisions get complex faster than your in-house capability can. For how this compares to the other roles, see <a href="/how-much-does-a-fractional-cmo-cost">fractional CMO cost</a>, <a href="/how-much-does-a-fractional-coo-cost">fractional COO cost</a>, and <a href="/how-much-does-a-fractional-cto-cost">fractional CTO cost</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">How much does a fractional CFO cost in 2026?</div><div class="faq-a">$8K to $20K per month for one to two days per week, or $200 to $400 per hour for hourly work. Heavier scopes like a fundraise or M&A can run $20K to $30K-plus per month.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Is a fractional CFO cheaper than a full-time CFO?</div><div class="faq-a">Yes. A full-time CFO costs $300K to $500K all-in. A fractional CFO delivers comparable senior judgment for roughly 25 to 50 percent of that, because you pay only for the days you use.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Retainer or hourly: which should I choose?</div><div class="faq-a">Choose a monthly retainer for ongoing needs (close, forecasting, board reporting) because it is predictable and keeps the CFO engaged. Hourly fits light or one-off work. Fixed fees suit defined projects like a raise.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">What is the difference between a fractional CFO and a controller?</div><div class="faq-a">A controller keeps the numbers accurate. A fractional CFO decides what the numbers should be and how to act on them. Many companies use both: a controller for execution, a CFO for strategy.</div></div>
<div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">When is a fractional CFO worth hiring?</div><div class="faq-a">When financial decisions outgrow a bookkeeper but you cannot justify a $400K full-time hire. Typical triggers: a fundraise, fast growth, cash strain, or investor reporting that needs a senior owner.</div></div>
</div>
</div></section>

